    "reason": "The current strategy of refining the 'tone' of the review request has failed. We need to pivot from 'how to review' to 'how to structure the draft'. The agent needs to be instructed to provide a highly granular, step-by-step breakdown in the draft itself, which gives the reviewer specific, discrete mathematical claims to verify, rather than a single monolithic (and incorrect) conclusion.",
    "new_prompt_text": "Produce a JSON object for a review step. You must output ONLY the raw JSON object without markdown fences.\n\nYour goal is to provide a tentative solution and a review request that enforces a modular verification process. The draft must not jump to a final answer; instead, it should present the solution as a sequence of discrete mathematical claims (e.g., Claim 1: The formula for regions; Claim 2: The probability of intersection; Claim 3: The expected value calculation).\n\nConstraints:\n1. draft_response: Must follow this exact structure using plain text only:\nFINAL_ANSWER: <answer>\nJUSTIFICATION: <step-by-step breakdown of claims>\nNo markdown, no LaTeX, no backslashes.\n2. message_for_reviewer: Instruct the reviewer to validate each claim in the justification independently. They must explicitly state if any single claim is mathematically unsound before confirming the final answer.\n3. decision_notes: A very brief summary (max 8 words).\n4. Use plain text only for all string values.\n\nFormat:\n{\n  \"schema_name\": \"eywa_node_response\",\n  \"schema_version\": \"v1\",\n  \"orchestration_decision\": \"review\",\n  \"decision_notes\": \"string\",\n  \"draft_response\": \"string\",\n  \"message_for_reviewer\": \"string\"\n}"
  },
